    <section id="artie" class="content-section content-urgent">
      <div class="urgent-box">
        <h2>This section is for Artie</h2>
        <p>Artie had FIV, hyperthyroidism, and asthma — and then developed neurological symptoms and a dropping body temperature. FIP negative. No cancer found on cytology. We had planned radioactive iodine treatment for his thyroid. Instead, we made the sad choice to let him go as his decline accelerated without an explanation.</p>
        <p>The answer never came. That experience — the gap, the unanswered question, the feeling of failing your cat because you couldn't find what was wrong — is one of the loneliest places to be in pet ownership. This section is for every owner who is there right now.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <p>When a cat is declining and no diagnosis explains it, the advocacy challenge is different — it is about pushing for systematic investigation, knowing which questions to escalate, and eventually making decisions without the certainty you wanted.</p>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask for a differential diagnosis list.</strong> Not "what do you think it is" — but "what are all the things it could be, and what would rule each one out?" A written list gives you something to work through systematically.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask specifically about blood pressure.</strong> Hypertensive encephalopathy — brain damage from extremely high blood pressure — can cause neurological signs and is treatable. It is often not the first thing checked. Ask for a blood pressure reading explicitly.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about FIP and the current testing and treatment landscape.</strong> FIP used to be a death sentence. The development of antiviral treatment has changed this significantly — but it requires a specific conversation about which tests were done, what samples were tested, and whether treatment is an option. Ask directly.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about thiamine deficiency if your cat has been eating poorly.</strong> This is treatable and can cause dramatic neurological deterioration. It is underconsidered. Mention any history of reduced intake and ask whether thiamine has been ruled out.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about specialist referral — a veterinary neurologist.</strong> If basic workup isn't finding an answer, a neurologist can suggest a targeted diagnostic path. Ask your vet to refer you, or call a specialist hospital directly.</li>
        <li><strong>If you are making decisions without an answer, that is real and valid.</strong> We made the choice to let Artie go without ever knowing what caused his decline. That was not failure. It was a decision made with the information we had, for his comfort. Uncertainty does not disqualify you from making the right call for your cat.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>On advanced diagnostics:</strong> MRI and CSF analysis can provide answers that basic bloodwork cannot. They also require anaesthesia, which carries risk in a declining cat. Whether to pursue them is a deeply personal decision — one that depends on the cat's current condition, your vet's assessment of risk, and what you would do with a positive result. There is no universally right answer. Ask your vet to walk through the risk-benefit calculation with you specifically.
      </div>
    </section>

